1
00:00:17,760 --> 00:00:19,600
(MACHINERY WHIRRING)

2
00:00:26,160 --> 00:00:29,360
DEEP AUTOMATED VOICE:
People of Earth, you stand alone.

3
00:00:30,120 --> 00:00:32,400
-(ALARM BLARING)
-AUTOMATED VOICE: Intruder alert.

4
00:00:32,480 --> 00:00:34,400
Intruder alert.

5
00:00:34,840 --> 00:00:36,800
-Intruder alert.
-(GRUNTING)

6
00:00:37,720 --> 00:00:39,480
Ah! Oh...

7
00:00:42,240 --> 00:00:43,840
(SHOUTING)

8
00:00:51,480 --> 00:00:53,120
(WHIRRING)

9
00:00:57,800 --> 00:00:58,840
(WHIRRING)

10
00:01:11,800 --> 00:01:13,720
(GRUNTING)

11
00:01:16,680 --> 00:01:18,200
(EXCLAIMS)

12
00:01:23,640 --> 00:01:25,200
Ah... Ah!

13
00:01:25,640 --> 00:01:28,160
Come here, spacesuit, come to Doctor.

14
00:01:30,160 --> 00:01:32,520
Ahh!

15
00:01:33,120 --> 00:01:34,360
(SHOUTING)

16
00:01:40,600 --> 00:01:42,120
(GRUNTING)

17
00:01:44,840 --> 00:01:46,360
Come on!

18
00:01:48,760 --> 00:01:50,240
(EXCLAIMING)

19
00:01:54,400 --> 00:01:56,760
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

20
00:02:36,320 --> 00:02:38,080
(OBJECT SCREAMING THROUGH AIR)

21
00:02:38,160 --> 00:02:39,160
DOCTOR: Whoa!

22
00:02:39,280 --> 00:02:41,160
(LOUD CRASH, CYCLIST SCREAMS)

23
00:02:41,240 --> 00:02:42,720
Oh!

24
00:03:01,680 --> 00:03:02,880
Hello?

25
00:03:04,720 --> 00:03:07,720
Hello? Hello, are you all right?

26
00:03:08,080 --> 00:03:09,400
(GROANING)

27
00:03:10,520 --> 00:03:13,640
Are you hurt? Did you fall?

28
00:03:15,680 --> 00:03:20,000
-Where did you fall from?
-(GROANING) The helmet.

29
00:03:20,120 --> 00:03:22,400
All right, just... Just let me...

30
00:03:23,880 --> 00:03:26,120
I don't want to hurt you.

31
00:03:27,480 --> 00:03:30,200
-Oh!
-I can't see. I'm blind.

32
00:03:30,280 --> 00:03:32,080
Oh no, love, you're not.

33
00:03:32,160 --> 00:03:35,000
I think you've just got your
helmet on backwards.

34
00:03:35,560 --> 00:03:36,800
How did you manage that?

35
00:03:36,880 --> 00:03:38,880
I got dressed in a hurry.

36
00:03:42,320 --> 00:03:43,960
(DOOR OPENING, CLOSING)

37
00:03:45,920 --> 00:03:48,080
Cyril, what are you doing awake?

38
00:03:48,160 --> 00:03:50,840
It's the moon's fault, apparently.
It's too "interesting”.

39
00:03:50,920 --> 00:03:53,080
-It's astronomy.
-Don't make up words.

40
00:03:53,280 --> 00:03:55,360
He's always making up things
and breathing.

41
00:03:55,440 --> 00:03:57,360
-Where's your father?
-In the garden.

42
00:03:57,600 --> 00:03:59,600
What's he doing in the garden?

43
00:03:59,680 --> 00:04:01,920
-Agriculture.
-LILY: You're not fooling anyone!

44
00:04:02,360 --> 00:04:06,000
Listen, Cyril, tell him that
I've borrowed Mr Goldsmith's car.

45
00:04:06,080 --> 00:04:09,440
That I found a space man in a field,
possibly an angel,

46
00:04:09,680 --> 00:04:11,720
but he's injured
and I can't get his helmet off,

47
00:04:11,800 --> 00:04:14,200
so I'm having to take him into town
to find a police telephone box.

48
00:04:14,280 --> 00:04:15,480
All right?

49
00:04:16,200 --> 00:04:17,800
-All right.
-Good boy!

50
00:04:22,200 --> 00:04:23,560
Was that your mother?

51
00:04:24,160 --> 00:04:26,640
-Where's she going?
-Out.

52
00:04:35,800 --> 00:04:36,840
(CRASHING)

53
00:04:36,920 --> 00:04:38,160
DOCTOR: Ow!

54
00:04:39,960 --> 00:04:41,280
(DOCTOR GROANING)

55
00:04:42,680 --> 00:04:47,120
-Did we just bump into something?
-No, no.

56
00:04:47,840 --> 00:04:50,280
We seemed to bump into
quite a lot of things.

57
00:04:50,360 --> 00:04:53,240
Well, a lot of things get in the way,
it's hardly my fault.

58
00:04:53,400 --> 00:04:55,800
You need to take that silly thing off.

59
00:04:56,160 --> 00:04:59,560
Can't, impact suit.
It's still repairing me.

60
00:04:59,920 --> 00:05:01,960
-Repairing you?
-Yeah, well, you know,

61
00:05:02,200 --> 00:05:04,120
that's the idea.

62
00:05:04,200 --> 00:05:06,720
Won't it repair you all back to front?

63
00:05:06,840 --> 00:05:09,760
-No, no.
-Well, that's good.

64
00:05:10,320 --> 00:05:14,120
-Oh, there's a streetlamp.
-Yes, I got that impression.

65
00:05:14,200 --> 00:05:15,480
Round this way.

66
00:05:16,280 --> 00:05:19,240
Don't you want me to take you
to hospital or something?

67
00:05:19,680 --> 00:05:21,560
You're welcome to come to our house.

68
00:05:21,640 --> 00:05:26,200
No, no, no, I'm fine.
I just need to find the...

69
00:05:26,520 --> 00:05:29,080
-uh, the key.
-Oh.

70
00:05:29,160 --> 00:05:32,240
Do you want me to do it with a pin?
I'm good with a pin.

71
00:05:32,400 --> 00:05:35,400
Multi-dimensional,
triple-encoded temporal-interface.

72
00:05:35,680 --> 00:05:39,000
Not really susceptible to pointy things.

73
00:05:39,080 --> 00:05:40,920
Oh! Ah!

74
00:05:41,120 --> 00:05:42,720
-Got it!
-Okay.

75
00:05:42,880 --> 00:05:46,240
Suddenly the last 900 years of
time travel seem that bit less secure.

76
00:05:46,320 --> 00:05:48,280
Thank you for taking care of me.

77
00:05:48,360 --> 00:05:50,800
You didn't have to, you know.
You've been very kind.

78
00:05:50,920 --> 00:05:53,400
Don't be silly. It's Christmas Eve.

79
00:05:53,680 --> 00:05:55,560
No one should be alone at Christmas.

80
00:05:55,720 --> 00:05:59,080
-What did you say your name was?
-Madge. Madge Arwell.

81
00:05:59,160 --> 00:06:01,960
If there's ever anything that
I can do for you, let me know.

82
00:06:02,040 --> 00:06:03,560
-How?
-I dunno.

83
00:06:03,640 --> 00:06:06,360
-Make a wish, that usually works.
-Does it?

84
00:06:06,480 --> 00:06:08,680
Well, it did for me.
You're here, aren't you?

85
00:06:08,800 --> 00:06:10,040
(BOTH LAUGHING)

86
00:06:10,240 --> 00:06:13,720
Oh, well, don't wait around here,
just off you go home.

87
00:06:13,800 --> 00:06:17,840
I'll just go and wait inside here.

88
00:06:20,240 --> 00:06:21,480
Ow!

89
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:24,880
Wrong one.
Do you think we could try again?

90
00:06:29,040 --> 00:06:32,400
You were a long time.
Been taking home strays, as usual?

91
00:06:32,680 --> 00:06:34,160
Just the one.

92
00:06:34,760 --> 00:06:38,760
What have you been reading?
Not the war again.

93
00:06:39,680 --> 00:06:43,000
If people keep reading about the war,
then it'll actually happen.

94
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:45,160
And then where will you be?

95
00:06:50,120 --> 00:06:52,120
(ENGINE SPUTTERING)

96
00:06:54,840 --> 00:06:58,320
Sir, Anderson's in a bad way.
Where are we?

97
00:06:58,600 --> 00:07:00,960
I don't know.
Somewhere over the Channel.

98
00:07:01,040 --> 00:07:02,360
What do I tell Anderson?

99
00:07:02,440 --> 00:07:06,160
Tell him... Tell him...
Tell him we're going home for Christmas.

100
00:07:06,920 --> 00:07:08,080
Yes, sir.

101
00:07:15,080 --> 00:07:16,760
I'm sorry, my love.

102
00:07:22,480 --> 00:07:24,320
(ENGINES SPUTTERING)

103
00:07:50,640 --> 00:07:53,800
-When's Father coming back?
-For Christmas, like he always does.

104
00:07:53,920 --> 00:07:55,560
Now, hurry up and think of something.

105
00:07:55,640 --> 00:07:57,920
But we're going to Uncle Digby's house.

106
00:07:58,000 --> 00:07:59,320
Will he be there?

107
00:07:59,720 --> 00:08:03,160
He will, won't he, Mother?
Daddy will be there?

108
00:08:04,440 --> 00:08:06,560
-Of course he will.
-See?

109
00:08:06,760 --> 00:08:08,560
Now, have you thought of anything?

110
00:08:08,640 --> 00:08:10,840
Um... Yep.

111
00:08:12,440 --> 00:08:14,560
Count of three, then. Make a wish.

112
00:08:15,040 --> 00:08:17,240
One, two, three.

113
00:08:28,080 --> 00:08:30,200
-Is it haunted?
-Is it draughty?

114
00:08:31,240 --> 00:08:32,440
Oh, this is no good.

115
00:08:32,520 --> 00:08:35,920
Where's Mr Cardew?
He was supposed to be here.

116
00:08:36,840 --> 00:08:38,080
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

117
00:08:38,160 --> 00:08:40,680
Maybe it's haunted
by the ghost of Uncle Digby.

118
00:08:41,120 --> 00:08:42,520
Uncle Digby is still alive.

119
00:08:43,200 --> 00:08:45,880
-He's in a home in Battersea.
-Mr Cardew!

120
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:49,640
-But why do we have to come here?
-Because of the bombing, stupid.

121
00:08:49,800 --> 00:08:51,840
I like the bombing. It's exciting.

122
00:08:53,600 --> 00:08:55,360
Will Father be here?

123
00:08:55,560 --> 00:08:57,600
Well, he will, won't he?
You said he'd meet us at the house.

124
00:08:57,680 --> 00:08:59,600
He'll be here. Of course he will.

125
00:08:59,680 --> 00:09:01,880
You don't need to keep asking about it.

126
00:09:01,960 --> 00:09:03,120
(DOOR UNLOCKING)

127
00:09:03,200 --> 00:09:04,400
Father!

128
00:09:04,640 --> 00:09:07,880
Sorry, it's the door,
it's developed a fault.

129
00:09:07,960 --> 00:09:10,440
Oh, hello? Mr Cardew?

130
00:09:14,440 --> 00:09:15,880
There we go!

131
00:09:15,960 --> 00:09:18,280
Well, come in, in you come.

132
00:09:20,240 --> 00:09:21,680
Mind your step.

133
00:09:21,760 --> 00:09:26,480
Now, don't worry, the back door is
still, broadly speaking, operational.

134
00:09:29,400 --> 00:09:32,040
Right, then, may I take your cases?

135
00:09:32,320 --> 00:09:33,640
-Thank you.
-Thank you.

136
00:09:33,720 --> 00:09:35,000
-Thank you.
-Lovely.

137
00:09:35,080 --> 00:09:37,120
Would you mind carrying them for me?
I need to show you round.

138
00:09:37,200 --> 00:09:39,600
Oh, no, wait. Who are you?

139
00:09:39,880 --> 00:09:42,560
-I'm the caretaker.
-But you're not Mr Cardew.

140
00:09:43,880 --> 00:09:45,560
-I agree.
-But I don't understand.

141
00:09:45,640 --> 00:09:48,000
-Are you the new caretaker?
-Usually called the Doctor.

142
00:09:48,080 --> 00:09:50,160
Or the Caretaker.
Or Get Off This Planet.

143
00:09:50,240 --> 00:09:53,240
Though, strictly speaking,
that probably isn't a name.

144
00:09:54,480 --> 00:09:55,960
-Hello, Madge Arwell.
-Hello.

145
00:09:56,360 --> 00:09:57,720
And Cyril Arwell.

146
00:09:58,400 --> 00:09:59,960
And Lily Arwell.

147
00:10:00,880 --> 00:10:03,520
Now, come on, come on, lots to see,
whistles top tour, take notes,

148
00:10:03,600 --> 00:10:04,640
there will be questions.

149
00:10:05,680 --> 00:10:07,080
Smaller sitting room.

150
00:10:07,160 --> 00:10:10,040
Just chairs.
A bit pointless without a television.

151
00:10:10,360 --> 00:10:12,560
So I made some repairs.

152
00:10:21,760 --> 00:10:22,840
I know!

153
00:10:22,920 --> 00:10:26,320
The kitchen. That's a cooker, probably,
and these are taps.

154
00:10:26,400 --> 00:10:29,320
Hot, cold, lemonade.

155
00:10:29,800 --> 00:10:32,440
-Lemonade?
-I know!

156
00:10:33,520 --> 00:10:34,920
Staircase.

157
00:10:36,440 --> 00:10:38,240
Seems to have broken down.

158
00:10:40,320 --> 00:10:41,360
We'll have to walk up.

159
00:10:41,440 --> 00:10:43,800
I sleep up there, stay away.
Beware of panthers.

160
00:10:44,720 --> 00:10:46,320
-Panthers?
-DOCTOR: They're terrifying!

161
00:10:46,400 --> 00:10:48,040
Have you never seen panthers?

162
00:10:48,760 --> 00:10:50,080
Cyril!

163
00:10:51,480 --> 00:10:55,480
Mum's bedroom, grown-up,
your basic boring.

164
00:10:57,520 --> 00:11:01,520
Lily and Cyril's room.
I'm going to be honest, masterpiece!

165
00:11:01,680 --> 00:11:03,480
The ultimate bedroom.

166
00:11:03,560 --> 00:11:06,000
A sciency-wiency work bench!
A jungle! A maze!

167
00:11:06,080 --> 00:11:09,040
A window disguised as a mirror.
A mirror disguised as a window.

168
00:11:09,120 --> 00:11:12,240
Selection of torches for
midnight feasts and secret reading,

169
00:11:12,320 --> 00:11:15,720
Zen garden, mysterious cupboard,
zone of tranquillity,

170
00:11:15,920 --> 00:11:18,680
rubber ball, dream tank,
exact model of the rest of the house

171
00:11:18,760 --> 00:11:20,480
not quite to scale, apologies.

172
00:11:20,560 --> 00:11:22,600
Dolls with comical expressions,

173
00:11:22,680 --> 00:11:26,600
the Magna Carta, a foot spa,
Cluedo, a yellow fort.

174
00:11:27,880 --> 00:11:29,280
Where are the beds?

175
00:11:29,520 --> 00:11:31,720
Well, I couldn't fit everything in,
there had to be sacrifices.

176
00:11:31,800 --> 00:11:34,560
Anyway, who needs beds
when you've got...

177
00:11:37,240 --> 00:11:38,360
hammocks!

178
00:11:39,480 --> 00:11:40,840
I know!

179
00:11:42,720 --> 00:11:44,720
-How do you get on?
-Watch and learn, kid.

180
00:11:47,960 --> 00:11:49,720
For God's sake!

181
00:11:51,760 --> 00:11:53,280
This hammock has developed a fault!

182
00:11:53,400 --> 00:11:56,600
Can you please stop talking,
can you please just stop?

183
00:11:58,560 --> 00:12:00,120
-Sorry.
-Children, go downstairs.

184
00:12:01,000 --> 00:12:02,200
-Why?
-Are we leaving?

185
00:12:02,280 --> 00:12:03,560
Yes! No.

186
00:12:04,040 --> 00:12:06,520
I don't know,
just please, go downstairs!

187
00:12:06,680 --> 00:12:08,480
You don't need to shout.

188
00:12:13,960 --> 00:12:18,080
-Why are you doing all this?
-I'm just trying to take care of things.

189
00:12:18,480 --> 00:12:21,200
-I'm the caretaker.
-That's not what caretakers do.

190
00:12:21,280 --> 00:12:23,400
Then why are they called caretakers?

191
00:12:24,120 --> 00:12:25,880
Their father's dead.

192
00:12:27,120 --> 00:12:29,880
-I'm sorry.
-Lily and Cyril's father,

193
00:12:30,160 --> 00:12:32,480
my husband, is dead
and they don't know yet.

194
00:12:32,560 --> 00:12:33,800
Because if I tell them now,

195
00:12:33,880 --> 00:12:36,480
then Christmas will always be what
took their father away from them

196
00:12:36,560 --> 00:12:39,320
and no one should have
to live like that.

197
00:12:41,040 --> 00:12:43,960
Of course, when the
Christmas period is over, I shall...

198
00:12:50,960 --> 00:12:53,360
I don't know why
I keep shouting at them.

199
00:12:53,520 --> 00:12:55,440
Because every time you see them happy,

200
00:12:55,520 --> 00:12:58,280
you remember how sad
they're going to be

201
00:12:59,560 --> 00:13:01,480
and it breaks your heart.

202
00:13:03,360 --> 00:13:04,760
LILY: Mother! Come and see!

203
00:13:04,840 --> 00:13:08,120
CYRIL: Mother, you've got to see this!
Come!

204
00:13:08,240 --> 00:13:10,240
Because what's the point in them
being happy now

205
00:13:10,320 --> 00:13:12,800
-if they're going to be sad later?
-CYRIL: Mother?

206
00:13:12,880 --> 00:13:14,200
LILY: Mother? Are you coming?

207
00:13:14,320 --> 00:13:16,280
The answer is, of course,

208
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:19,360
because they are going to be sad later.

209
00:13:24,760 --> 00:13:26,560
Now, we'd better get downstairs.

210
00:13:26,800 --> 00:13:29,640
I think they may have found
the main sitting room.

211
00:13:30,000 --> 00:13:33,280
-CYRIL: Mother!
-I repaired it.

212
00:13:41,560 --> 00:13:42,680
Ha.

213
00:13:42,960 --> 00:13:44,880
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWING)

214
00:13:56,120 --> 00:13:57,200
I know!

215
00:13:57,280 --> 00:13:59,080
Look at that present!

216
00:14:00,920 --> 00:14:03,000
-It's for me!
-It says it's for all of us.

217
00:14:03,720 --> 00:14:06,560
I'm youngest, I get to open it first!

218
00:14:06,640 --> 00:14:08,160
Doesn't say who it's from.

219
00:14:08,240 --> 00:14:10,320
Mother, who left this here?

220
00:14:13,840 --> 00:14:17,280
That man is quite ridiculous.
You must stay away from him.

221
00:14:17,360 --> 00:14:19,560
-I like him.
-I like him, too.

222
00:14:19,840 --> 00:14:22,760
And it's a nice tree, isn't it?

223
00:14:24,280 --> 00:14:27,280
-It's the best tree in the world.
-Yes.

224
00:14:29,320 --> 00:14:31,120
Yes, I suppose it is.

225
00:14:32,240 --> 00:14:34,440
Say it, Mother, go on, please?

226
00:14:34,800 --> 00:14:37,040
Say the thing you always say.

227
00:14:39,880 --> 00:14:45,200
This Christmas is going to be
the best Christmas ever.

228
00:14:52,720 --> 00:14:54,480
(ETHEREAL VOICES WHISPERING, INDISTINCT)

229
00:15:06,360 --> 00:15:09,720
Lily? Lily, can you sleep?

230
00:15:11,320 --> 00:15:12,720
-Lily?
-Shut up!

231
00:15:13,080 --> 00:15:14,960
What do you think that present is?

232
00:15:15,120 --> 00:15:17,200
We could just sneak down
and have a look.

233
00:15:17,560 --> 00:15:18,960
Go to sleep!

234
00:15:24,400 --> 00:15:25,960
(ETHEREAL VOICES WHISPERING)

235
00:15:28,400 --> 00:15:29,840
(ELECTRICAL BUZZING)

236
00:15:31,480 --> 00:15:33,000
(HAMMERING)

237
00:15:33,400 --> 00:15:35,200
(ELECTRICAL BUZZING)

238
00:15:47,120 --> 00:15:49,240
(ETHEREAL VOICES WHISPERING)

239
00:15:51,640 --> 00:15:53,280
(ELECTRICAL BUZZING)

240
00:16:10,920 --> 00:16:12,800
(ELECTRICITY CRACKLING)

241
00:16:30,560 --> 00:16:32,160
(ETHEREAL VOICES WHISPERING)

242
00:16:45,760 --> 00:16:49,320
-You were lying about the panthers.
-Famous last words.

243
00:16:49,400 --> 00:16:51,080
Why have you got a phone box
in your room?

244
00:16:51,720 --> 00:16:55,400
It's not a phone box, it's my wardrobe.

245
00:16:55,640 --> 00:16:58,040
I've just painted it
to look like a phone box.

246
00:16:58,800 --> 00:17:00,360
What are you doing?

247
00:17:00,440 --> 00:17:02,960
-Rewiring.
-Why would you rewire a wardrobe?

248
00:17:03,040 --> 00:17:04,920
Have you seen the way I dress?

249
00:17:11,400 --> 00:17:14,440
Who are you? Really, who are you?

250
00:17:17,480 --> 00:17:18,960
Your brother, where is he?

251
00:17:32,760 --> 00:17:34,520
(WIND GUSTING)

252
00:18:14,680 --> 00:18:16,880
(ETHEREAL VOICES WHISPERING)

253
00:18:35,160 --> 00:18:36,560
Still in bed, asleep.

254
00:18:36,840 --> 00:18:39,720
Okay. Faulty then.

255
00:19:07,080 --> 00:19:08,680
(VOICES WHISPERING)

256
00:19:11,720 --> 00:19:12,880
(GASPS)

257
00:19:23,520 --> 00:19:25,440
(PANTING)

258
00:19:26,280 --> 00:19:27,600
(BEEPING)

259
00:19:29,200 --> 00:19:30,680
You're sure he's still in bed?

260
00:20:01,400 --> 00:20:02,960
-See?
-(SHUSHING)

261
00:20:11,960 --> 00:20:13,600
Oh, he's good.

262
00:20:14,520 --> 00:20:17,960
The old bear and duvet, eh? Classic.

263
00:20:22,080 --> 00:20:23,640
Cyril!

264
00:20:24,400 --> 00:20:27,680
What's happening?
I hope... What is that?

265
00:20:27,760 --> 00:20:29,480
With me, quickly, come on!

266
00:20:31,120 --> 00:20:35,120
That's it, in you come.
Bit cold, never mind.

267
00:20:35,200 --> 00:20:37,560
Cyril? Cyril?

268
00:20:39,600 --> 00:20:40,720
Where are we?

269
00:20:40,800 --> 00:20:44,400
In a forest, in a box,
in a sitting room. Pay attention.

270
00:20:45,080 --> 00:20:47,320
-He's about twenty minutes ahead of us.
-But we just saw him.

271
00:20:47,400 --> 00:20:49,880
Time moves differently
across the dimensional planes.

272
00:20:49,960 --> 00:20:52,560
What do they teach you
in schools these days?

273
00:20:53,280 --> 00:20:54,800
But I don't understand where we are!

274
00:20:54,880 --> 00:20:56,800
We've gone through
a dimensional portal...

275
00:20:58,800 --> 00:20:59,800
thingy.

276
00:20:59,880 --> 00:21:01,200
Well, what's that supposed to be?

277
00:21:01,280 --> 00:21:03,040
-Where did it come from?
-It was a present.

278
00:21:03,120 --> 00:21:04,800
And it wasn't supposed
to be opened till Christmas Day.

279
00:21:04,880 --> 00:21:08,040
Honestly, who opens
their Christmas presents early?

280
00:21:09,200 --> 00:21:11,840
Okay, shut up, everyone!

281
00:21:11,960 --> 00:21:13,640
(VOICES WHISPERING)

282
00:21:19,280 --> 00:21:21,440
(WHISPERING GROWS LOUDER)

283
00:21:36,440 --> 00:21:38,760
I don't understand. Is this place real?

284
00:21:39,320 --> 00:21:41,520
-Is it fairyland?
-Fairyland?

285
00:21:41,600 --> 00:21:43,600
Oh, grow up, Lily!

286
00:21:43,960 --> 00:21:45,440
Fairyland looks completely different.

287
00:21:45,520 --> 00:21:51,040
Now, these are Cyril's footprints
and these are the ones he was following.

288
00:21:51,320 --> 00:21:52,800
Notice anything?

289
00:21:53,160 --> 00:21:55,320
The other footprints are getting bigger.

290
00:21:55,400 --> 00:21:56,560
Yes.

291
00:21:57,640 --> 00:22:01,280
Whatever your brother's following,
it's growing.

292
00:22:07,280 --> 00:22:09,640
Well, then, we have to get after him!

293
00:22:13,720 --> 00:22:16,080
It's okay, you're fine. Don't worry.

294
00:22:16,160 --> 00:22:19,240
-Is that tree alive?
-Of course it's alive, it's a tree.

295
00:22:19,840 --> 00:22:22,680
-But is it dangerous?
-Well, every rose has its thorns.

296
00:22:24,440 --> 00:22:26,560
They're like Christmas tree decorations.

297
00:22:26,640 --> 00:22:29,800
Yeah, naturally occurring
Christmas trees.

298
00:22:31,280 --> 00:22:33,120
Oh, how cool is that?

299
00:22:33,280 --> 00:22:34,360
I don't understand.

300
00:22:34,440 --> 00:22:36,680
It's a big universe.
Everything happens somewhere.

301
00:22:36,800 --> 00:22:40,520
Call it a coincidence,
call it an idea echoing among the stars.

302
00:22:40,600 --> 00:22:44,480
Personally, I call it a brilliant idea
for a Christmas trip.

303
00:22:44,560 --> 00:22:47,360
-Or it should have...
-(WIND GUSTING)

304
00:22:47,440 --> 00:22:48,680
...been.

305
00:22:49,920 --> 00:22:51,080
(VOICES WHISPERING)

306
00:22:51,160 --> 00:22:54,320
Do you know the difference between
wind and trees talking to each other?

307
00:22:54,480 --> 00:22:55,600
What?

308
00:23:01,200 --> 00:23:02,440
No wind.

309
00:23:03,200 --> 00:23:06,640
I've been here many times but
I've never heard the trees so active.

310
00:23:06,720 --> 00:23:08,400
Something's wrong.

311
00:23:13,360 --> 00:23:15,080
What are you doing?

312
00:23:16,840 --> 00:23:18,560
What are you up to?

313
00:23:27,600 --> 00:23:28,840
I'm sorry, Lily, I really am,

314
00:23:28,920 --> 00:23:31,720
but there is something
very wrong in this forest

315
00:23:32,520 --> 00:23:34,520
and your brother's right
in the middle of it.

316
00:23:34,920 --> 00:23:37,920
Lily and Cyril Arwell, where are you?

317
00:24:05,680 --> 00:24:07,480
(TREES WHISPERING)

318
00:25:06,400 --> 00:25:07,600
(GASPS)

319
00:25:43,760 --> 00:25:45,160
Why would you bring us to this place?

320
00:25:45,240 --> 00:25:46,480
It was supposed to be a treat.

321
00:25:46,560 --> 00:25:48,240
This is one of the
safest planets I know.

322
00:25:48,320 --> 00:25:49,680
There's never anything dangerous here.

323
00:25:49,800 --> 00:25:50,800
(THUDDING)

324
00:25:54,080 --> 00:25:56,680
There are sentences
I should just keep away from.

325
00:25:58,960 --> 00:25:59,960
(THUDDING)

326
00:26:05,520 --> 00:26:06,520
(THUDDING)

327
00:26:12,440 --> 00:26:13,680
(CRIES OUT)

328
00:26:23,280 --> 00:26:24,400
Oh!

329
00:26:27,760 --> 00:26:31,080
MAN: (ON PA) This tree farm is
private property, you are trespassing.

330
00:26:45,320 --> 00:26:47,440
-Unarmed, sir.
-What the hell are you doing here?

331
00:26:47,520 --> 00:26:50,280
No, wait armed. No, unarmed.

332
00:26:51,200 --> 00:26:53,600
Sorry, sir. She's wearing wool, sir.

333
00:26:53,920 --> 00:26:55,440
The natural fabrics,
they interfere with the...

334
00:26:55,520 --> 00:26:58,720
Please say we can tell the difference
between wool and side arms.

335
00:26:58,800 --> 00:27:00,160
We can tell the difference, sir.

336
00:27:00,600 --> 00:27:02,360
-Can we?
-Not always, sir, no.

337
00:27:05,040 --> 00:27:06,320
What are you doing here?

338
00:27:06,400 --> 00:27:09,240
And do you understand what is
about to happen in this forest?

339
00:27:09,360 --> 00:27:13,040
-I was just...
-Sir, I think she's a time traveller.

340
00:27:13,120 --> 00:27:14,960
And we're sure it's not her cardigan?

341
00:27:15,160 --> 00:27:16,720
MADGE: Who are you?

342
00:27:17,680 --> 00:27:19,440
It was Christmas!

343
00:27:20,640 --> 00:27:22,040
(WEEPING)

344
00:27:48,040 --> 00:27:49,040
(DOOR CREAKING)

345
00:27:51,560 --> 00:27:52,560
(SLAMS SHUT)

346
00:27:54,720 --> 00:27:56,040
It's just irresponsible!

347
00:27:56,120 --> 00:27:57,400
How can you do this to my brother?

348
00:27:57,480 --> 00:27:58,760
It was meant to be a supervised trip.

349
00:27:58,840 --> 00:28:00,160
-To the future.
-The future, yes.

350
00:28:00,240 --> 00:28:02,120
-The future on a different planet.
-Oh, yes, very different.

351
00:28:02,200 --> 00:28:03,640
Where Christmas trees just happen?

352
00:28:03,720 --> 00:28:07,120
Well, sort of Christmas trees,
they're not really Christmas trees.

353
00:28:34,960 --> 00:28:36,920
Oh, look at that!

354
00:28:38,080 --> 00:28:40,280
-What? Are we going in?
-Well, Cyril did.

355
00:28:43,160 --> 00:28:44,520
Interesting.

356
00:28:45,440 --> 00:28:48,040
What's that?
What's that statue, what is it?

357
00:28:48,120 --> 00:28:51,720
-It's like a king.
-A king, possibly, but not a statue.

358
00:28:52,680 --> 00:28:53,680
(GASPS)

359
00:28:54,080 --> 00:28:55,520
Look at the floor.

360
00:28:55,600 --> 00:28:58,280
This is what Cyril was following.
The growing thing.

361
00:28:58,360 --> 00:29:00,200
Hatched from the bauble on a tree.

362
00:29:00,280 --> 00:29:02,760
Grew to this size
in less than an hour, I'd say.

363
00:29:02,920 --> 00:29:05,360
Ooh, impressive.

364
00:29:06,040 --> 00:29:07,680
And so is this building.

365
00:29:08,480 --> 00:29:11,880
Yes, it's grown, see?
This building, it isn't a building,

366
00:29:12,080 --> 00:29:14,520
it's a group of trees grown in
the shape of a building,

367
00:29:14,600 --> 00:29:16,040
disguised as a building.

368
00:29:16,120 --> 00:29:21,200
Ooh, clever, I love clever.
Clever old forest.

369
00:29:21,400 --> 00:29:23,200
So, a forest grows a building.

370
00:29:23,280 --> 00:29:24,840
-Why would it do that, Lily?
-I don't know.

371
00:29:24,920 --> 00:29:27,840
-Why is there honey in a honey trap?
-Because it's a trap?

372
00:29:27,920 --> 00:29:31,000
Exactly. Thing about people,
we can never resist a door.

373
00:29:32,000 --> 00:29:35,720
So this is a trap?
We've just walked straight into a trap?

374
00:29:35,800 --> 00:29:40,000
A people trap. Question is,
why does a forest need people?

375
00:29:43,120 --> 00:29:44,640
We should go!
We have to get out of here.

376
00:29:44,720 --> 00:29:46,000
Except?

377
00:29:46,760 --> 00:29:48,520
Except Cyril's here.

378
00:29:53,040 --> 00:29:54,960
So let's find Cyril.

379
00:29:58,880 --> 00:30:00,240
DROXIL: Ma'am, please stop crying.

380
00:30:00,320 --> 00:30:02,600
I can't interrogate you
while you're crying.

381
00:30:02,680 --> 00:30:04,360
This is a military engagement!

382
00:30:04,440 --> 00:30:06,720
There's no crying
in military engagements!

383
00:30:06,800 --> 00:30:08,040
(SOBBING)

384
00:30:09,640 --> 00:30:12,520
-Corporal Ven-Garr, are you...
-I'm fine, sir.

385
00:30:13,280 --> 00:30:15,040
What is wrong with you?

386
00:30:15,120 --> 00:30:18,120
I have mother issues, sir.
It's all on file.

387
00:30:18,440 --> 00:30:20,320
It won't affect the performance of
my duties.

388
00:30:20,880 --> 00:30:24,360
Um, sir, with regret,
I'm going to have to lower my gun.

389
00:30:24,560 --> 00:30:26,640
-Why?
-She is a crying,

390
00:30:26,720 --> 00:30:29,080
unarmed female civilian.

391
00:30:29,160 --> 00:30:30,480
I'm thinking of the visual.

392
00:30:31,240 --> 00:30:32,640
Nobody's looking.

393
00:30:33,000 --> 00:30:34,880
BILLIS: Doesn't mean there's no visual.

394
00:30:34,960 --> 00:30:37,320
That's exactly what
"nobody's looking" means.

395
00:30:37,400 --> 00:30:39,960
-It means there's no visual.
-(SOBBING)

396
00:30:40,160 --> 00:30:42,760
I'm sorry, sir, it's under control.

397
00:30:42,840 --> 00:30:44,800
(COCKING GUN)
Do you want me to shoot her, sir?

398
00:30:44,880 --> 00:30:48,120
-Oh, this visual's deteriorating, sir.
-Shut up!

399
00:30:48,880 --> 00:30:49,920
(GUN POWERS DOWN)

400
00:30:50,000 --> 00:30:51,440
What are you doing?

401
00:30:51,840 --> 00:30:54,320
I am respecting her as a woman, sir.

402
00:30:54,400 --> 00:30:59,040
Oh, for... Okay.
We're putting our guns on the ground.

403
00:31:00,080 --> 00:31:01,120
(GUNS POWERING DOWN)

404
00:31:01,200 --> 00:31:05,560
Okay? Happy now?
We're stepping away from our guns.

405
00:31:06,520 --> 00:31:08,600
Now can we interrogate you?

406
00:31:09,640 --> 00:31:12,920
We're from Androzani Major,
the year is 5345,

407
00:31:13,000 --> 00:31:14,160
and we mean you no harm.

408
00:31:15,520 --> 00:31:19,000
-Where are you from?
-England, 1941.

409
00:31:19,440 --> 00:31:21,120
And there's a war on.

410
00:31:24,600 --> 00:31:28,640
Oh, crying's ever so useful, isn't it?

411
00:31:28,720 --> 00:31:31,680
If you say so. But there's nothing
you could say that would convince me

412
00:31:31,760 --> 00:31:33,960
-you'd ever use that gun.
-Really?

413
00:31:34,600 --> 00:31:37,240
Well, I'm looking for my children!

414
00:31:39,480 --> 00:31:40,800
Cyril?

415
00:31:43,120 --> 00:31:44,720
Cyril? Can you hear me?

416
00:31:46,160 --> 00:31:48,080
Cyril? Cyril!

417
00:31:49,080 --> 00:31:50,280
Cyril, can you hear me?

418
00:31:50,360 --> 00:31:51,680
Oh, of course, it's wood.

419
00:31:51,760 --> 00:31:53,440
-It's rubbish at wood!
-It doesn't look like wood.

420
00:31:53,520 --> 00:31:55,640
It's disguised wood.
Have you been listening?

421
00:31:55,720 --> 00:31:57,080
But how can trees grow into a building?

422
00:31:57,160 --> 00:31:58,560
Oh, never underestimate a tree, Lily.

423
00:31:58,640 --> 00:32:01,200
I met the Forest of Cheem once,
she fancied me.

424
00:32:04,920 --> 00:32:06,320
-Look at that!
-Busy, actually.

425
00:32:06,400 --> 00:32:09,960
-Yes, I know, it's wood, get over it!
-But there are stars.

426
00:32:10,040 --> 00:32:12,400
-There are stars coming out.
-Yes, that does happen, Lily.

427
00:32:12,480 --> 00:32:14,400
-Cyril!
-Yes, but out of the trees.

428
00:32:20,400 --> 00:32:21,840
What is that?

429
00:32:22,920 --> 00:32:24,400
Life force.

430
00:32:25,720 --> 00:32:31,320
Pure life force, just singing.

431
00:32:33,000 --> 00:32:37,120
It's beautiful.
Doesn't it make you want to cry?

432
00:32:39,720 --> 00:32:41,720
Crying when you're happy.

433
00:32:41,800 --> 00:32:45,160
Ah, good for you, that's so human.

434
00:32:45,920 --> 00:32:47,160
-(RUMBLING)
-What's that?

435
00:32:47,240 --> 00:32:48,640
What is it? Tell me, what?

436
00:32:48,720 --> 00:32:50,920
Cyril! Can you hear me?

437
00:33:10,840 --> 00:33:14,080
(FOOTSTEPS THUMPING)

438
00:33:14,240 --> 00:33:16,000
Oh, my God!

439
00:33:17,120 --> 00:33:18,520
Oh, my God!

440
00:33:25,040 --> 00:33:26,360
What is all this?

441
00:33:27,040 --> 00:33:29,360
Is it some kind of cockpit?

442
00:33:30,280 --> 00:33:31,720
My husband's a pilot.

443
00:33:31,880 --> 00:33:33,120
It drives the platform.

444
00:33:33,200 --> 00:33:35,000
I don't understand, how did I get here?

445
00:33:35,080 --> 00:33:37,600
-You tell us, ma"am.
-I'm looking for my children.

446
00:33:37,680 --> 00:33:39,720
There's nobody else in this forest,
there can't be.

447
00:33:40,000 --> 00:33:42,680
Well, she found her way in,
maybe her kids did, too.

448
00:33:42,880 --> 00:33:45,080
-Then God help them.
-Why do you say that?

449
00:33:45,160 --> 00:33:47,680
We can do a scan for life forms,
we can detect people,

450
00:33:47,760 --> 00:33:48,840
even though they're far away...

451
00:33:48,920 --> 00:33:50,200
-You mean like RDF, radar?
-Yeah.

452
00:33:50,280 --> 00:33:52,520
Well, then please stop
patronising me and get on with it.

453
00:33:52,600 --> 00:33:54,000
Yes, ma'am.

454
00:33:54,720 --> 00:33:56,480
Why did you say God help my children?

455
00:33:56,560 --> 00:33:58,920
This forest is about to be harvested.

456
00:33:59,440 --> 00:34:00,440
Harvested?

457
00:34:00,520 --> 00:34:04,200
Androzani trees,
greatest fuel source ever.

458
00:34:04,800 --> 00:34:07,720
The entire area is being
melted down for battery fluid.

459
00:34:07,800 --> 00:34:09,600
Melted down? How do you melt a forest?

460
00:34:09,680 --> 00:34:10,880
Acid rain.

461
00:34:11,200 --> 00:34:12,680
The satellites are in position.

462
00:34:12,760 --> 00:34:16,280
Anyone still out there in five minutes
is going to burn.

463
00:34:21,800 --> 00:34:24,880
-(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)
-Caretaker, it's coming!

464
00:34:24,960 --> 00:34:26,080
-Open it!
-I'm trying!

465
00:34:26,160 --> 00:34:27,320
-Open it!
-I'm trying!

466
00:34:27,400 --> 00:34:28,640
(DOOR UNLOCKS)

467
00:34:30,520 --> 00:34:32,160
-That wasn't me.
-It doesn't matter!

468
00:34:38,960 --> 00:34:41,120
What's wrong with him, Caretaker,
is he dead?

469
00:34:41,960 --> 00:34:44,160
It's okay, he's just unconscious.

470
00:34:45,240 --> 00:34:48,120
So, what are you, then?
Not a king, a queen.

471
00:34:48,840 --> 00:34:50,480
The Queen Bee of the forest?

472
00:34:51,920 --> 00:34:54,000
Caretaker! Look!

473
00:34:57,160 --> 00:34:59,040
-It's like...
-Like what?

474
00:35:00,840 --> 00:35:03,520
Like the life force
is leaving the forest.

475
00:35:11,440 --> 00:35:13,200
What are they doing? Stop them!

476
00:35:14,960 --> 00:35:16,880
-(WHIRRING)
-Oh, aliens made of wood?

477
00:35:16,960 --> 00:35:19,240
This was always going to happen,
you know.

478
00:35:20,080 --> 00:35:21,080
Um...

479
00:35:22,920 --> 00:35:24,120
It's okay.

480
00:35:25,440 --> 00:35:28,080
I think they just want to talk to us.

481
00:35:32,480 --> 00:35:33,960
They're scared.

482
00:35:36,240 --> 00:35:37,560
Can't you hear them?

483
00:35:37,640 --> 00:35:40,480
The trees are screaming,
can't you hear?

484
00:35:41,920 --> 00:35:44,120
No, but you can.

485
00:35:44,880 --> 00:35:46,160
You're connected to them.

486
00:35:46,280 --> 00:35:49,600
Okay, picking up life signs
about half a mile away.

487
00:35:49,800 --> 00:35:52,200
Can we go to them?
Can we move this thing?

488
00:35:52,360 --> 00:35:54,120
I'm not trained, ma'am. Those two are.

489
00:35:54,200 --> 00:35:57,160
-I can't trust them.
-And I can't drive the platform, ma'am.

490
00:35:57,400 --> 00:35:59,040
It looks a little like a plane.

491
00:35:59,120 --> 00:36:01,800
My husband flies a plane,
he took me up once.

492
00:36:01,880 --> 00:36:03,760
It takes years of training.

493
00:36:04,720 --> 00:36:07,520
Scanning for an audio connection,
we might be able to hear them.

494
00:36:07,600 --> 00:36:10,680
AUTOMATED VOICE: Acid rain alert
five minute warning.

495
00:36:10,800 --> 00:36:12,120
Prepare for beam-out.

496
00:36:12,200 --> 00:36:14,960
I'm so sorry,
you have to find a way out!

497
00:36:15,040 --> 00:36:16,400
-AUTOMATED VOICE: Evacuate.
-Acid fall is coming.

498
00:36:16,480 --> 00:36:17,920
You won't last two minutes.

499
00:36:18,000 --> 00:36:19,280
-Evacuate.
-Don't go!

500
00:36:19,360 --> 00:36:22,120
No, please wait. No!
What am I going to do?

501
00:36:22,360 --> 00:36:25,200
-Evacuate. Evacuate.
-Where have you gone?

502
00:36:25,280 --> 00:36:27,280
Acid fall in five minutes,

503
00:36:27,360 --> 00:36:30,000
unauthorised personnel
will be incinerated.

504
00:36:30,160 --> 00:36:32,000
(BEEPING)

505
00:36:32,080 --> 00:36:33,600
(LOUDSPEAKER SWITCHING ON)

506
00:36:33,840 --> 00:36:35,800
LILY: Why have the stars left the trees?

507
00:36:36,000 --> 00:36:37,640
CYRIL: I think they're...

508
00:36:37,840 --> 00:36:40,600
Just concentrate. What are they doing?

509
00:36:42,240 --> 00:36:44,880
Evacuating. They're evacuating.

510
00:36:45,000 --> 00:36:48,960
-Why?
-They're frightened of the rain.

511
00:36:49,760 --> 00:36:51,560
The rain that burns.

512
00:36:57,760 --> 00:37:00,920
LILY: Caretaker, please explain.
I'm frightened.

513
00:37:01,280 --> 00:37:03,960
Those stars, they're pure life force.

514
00:37:04,040 --> 00:37:07,440
Souls, if you like.
And they're trying to escape

515
00:37:08,080 --> 00:37:10,600
because they think their home
is going to burn.

516
00:37:10,840 --> 00:37:12,880
LILY: Why can't they just float up
into the sky?

517
00:37:12,960 --> 00:37:15,600
They need to travel inside
a living thing.

518
00:37:16,600 --> 00:37:17,920
Inside Cyril.

519
00:37:18,120 --> 00:37:19,480
See, this...

520
00:37:19,760 --> 00:37:22,200
(BUZZING)

521
00:37:22,880 --> 00:37:25,640
It's not a crown, it's a relay.

522
00:37:26,560 --> 00:37:28,960
They're turning your brother
into a lifeboat!

523
00:37:29,360 --> 00:37:31,360
That's what this place is for, then?

524
00:37:31,440 --> 00:37:33,240
It's an escape plan, is that it?

525
00:37:34,760 --> 00:37:37,240
Don't you harm him.
Do not touch that child!

526
00:37:38,400 --> 00:37:40,200
(IN DEEP VOICE)
Your coming was foretold.

527
00:37:40,280 --> 00:37:42,360
Oh, my God, what is that?
Why does he sound like that?

528
00:37:42,560 --> 00:37:44,000
Oh, hello!

529
00:37:44,400 --> 00:37:47,200
-Are we lip-synching now?
-We had faith.

530
00:37:47,400 --> 00:37:50,600
-Your coming was foretold.
-There's no such thing as foretelling.

531
00:37:50,680 --> 00:37:54,600
-Trust a time traveller.
-We waited and you came.

532
00:37:54,800 --> 00:37:59,400
So you've got an escape plan,
why aren't you escaping?

533
00:37:59,560 --> 00:38:01,040
The child is weak.

534
00:38:01,120 --> 00:38:03,920
-You mean, he's a child.
-No, he is weak.

535
00:38:04,200 --> 00:38:08,120
The forest cannot live in him.
But there are others.

536
00:38:08,440 --> 00:38:13,160
There certainly are, and the good
thing is I look great in a hat.

537
00:38:13,880 --> 00:38:18,640
-So, let's get this thing off, eh?
-You are also weak.

538
00:38:18,720 --> 00:38:22,040
I'm really not.
Let's save a forest, eh, Cyril?

539
00:38:22,120 --> 00:38:24,880
You are not the one. You are weak.

540
00:38:25,200 --> 00:38:26,800
I'm really not!

541
00:38:28,800 --> 00:38:30,320
(SCREAMING)

542
00:38:31,200 --> 00:38:33,240
Let go of it, just let go.

543
00:38:34,240 --> 00:38:37,080
Let go of it! Let go!
Please just drop it.

544
00:38:37,160 --> 00:38:38,160
I can't!

545
00:38:42,400 --> 00:38:44,680
Oh, it's funny, isn't it?

546
00:38:45,520 --> 00:38:49,600
-It's sort of tingly.
-Tingly?

547
00:38:52,880 --> 00:38:54,480
(IN DEEP VOICE)
She is strong. But she is young.

548
00:38:54,560 --> 00:38:55,760
(GASPS)

549
00:38:58,600 --> 00:39:01,440
She's strong, I'm weak. Interesting.

550
00:39:01,840 --> 00:39:03,280
CYRIL: (NORMAL VOICE) Mummy?

551
00:39:04,160 --> 00:39:06,680
Cyril, it's all right, it's me.

552
00:39:07,200 --> 00:39:11,280
Mummy isn't here,
but we're going home to her right now.

553
00:39:12,080 --> 00:39:13,880
-Aren't we, Caretaker?
-(THUNDER RUMBLING)

554
00:39:15,000 --> 00:39:16,840
(RAIN FALLING)

555
00:39:16,920 --> 00:39:19,800
No, I don't think we are.

556
00:39:23,800 --> 00:39:25,560
The rain that burns.

557
00:39:27,160 --> 00:39:28,480
Acid rain.

558
00:39:33,240 --> 00:39:36,520
DOCTOR: We have to get out of
this forest, we're in terrible danger.

559
00:39:37,320 --> 00:39:39,600
This tower won't protect us for long.

560
00:39:40,080 --> 00:39:42,520
CYRIL: Where's Mummy?
LILY: She's coming.

561
00:39:43,040 --> 00:39:47,720
You know she's coming, because she
she always comes, doesn't she?

562
00:39:48,800 --> 00:39:52,840
Cyril, the way we came here,
that door won't stay open forever.

563
00:39:53,200 --> 00:39:55,680
Now, I'm not even sure if I can
get us through the forest safely,

564
00:39:55,760 --> 00:39:59,320
but if we're going to have
any chance at all,

565
00:39:59,680 --> 00:40:01,280
we have to go now.

566
00:40:02,920 --> 00:40:05,080
No. We wait for Mummy.

567
00:40:05,400 --> 00:40:07,080
Mummy always comes.

568
00:40:07,160 --> 00:40:09,720
Not this time, Cyril. I'm sorry.

569
00:40:10,200 --> 00:40:11,640
-But not this time.
-(RUMBLING)

570
00:40:18,200 --> 00:40:19,600
What's that?

571
00:40:20,440 --> 00:40:21,920
It's an Androzani Harvester, but...

572
00:40:22,000 --> 00:40:23,320
You recognise that thing?

573
00:40:23,400 --> 00:40:25,720
More to the point,

574
00:40:25,800 --> 00:40:29,400
I think I recognise the driving!

575
00:40:31,720 --> 00:40:33,320
(DOCTOR LAUGHING)

576
00:40:33,400 --> 00:40:35,000
Madge has entered the forest!

577
00:40:36,920 --> 00:40:40,400
Come on, Madge, you can do it.
You go, girl!

578
00:40:40,520 --> 00:40:43,320
-Shut up, you ridiculous oaf!
-DOCTOR: Come on.

579
00:40:43,720 --> 00:40:46,200
This way, you can do it you can do it!

580
00:40:46,560 --> 00:40:48,760
Excellent driving, hello!

581
00:40:49,200 --> 00:40:50,840
-Caretaker?
-Yes!

582
00:40:50,920 --> 00:40:53,000
-You're fired!
-Oh.

583
00:40:58,200 --> 00:41:01,240
Whoa! Whoa, whoa!

584
00:41:02,800 --> 00:41:04,200
(CRASHING)

585
00:41:04,280 --> 00:41:06,440
It's okay, she's fine, don't worry.

586
00:41:06,800 --> 00:41:08,640
Stay here, just stay here.

587
00:41:09,640 --> 00:41:11,040
Madge? Madge?

588
00:41:13,960 --> 00:41:17,600
-You okay?
-Stay inside, the rain is frightful!

589
00:41:18,080 --> 00:41:20,120
Lily? Cyril?

590
00:41:25,880 --> 00:41:27,640
-Cyril!
-Mum!

591
00:41:27,720 --> 00:41:28,800
Lily!

592
00:41:29,440 --> 00:41:30,440
(SIGHING)

593
00:41:31,840 --> 00:41:36,160
What were you doing?
How dare you leave the house?

594
00:41:36,320 --> 00:41:39,240
Cyril, what have I told you about
opening your presents early?

595
00:41:39,400 --> 00:41:40,440
Sorry, Mummy.

596
00:41:40,520 --> 00:41:42,600
Something like this
was bound to happen.

597
00:41:42,680 --> 00:41:43,680
(GASPS)

598
00:41:45,880 --> 00:41:48,280
-Oh, what are those?
-You have to stay away from it.

599
00:41:48,400 --> 00:41:51,800
-You have to stay back.
-Oh, that's beautiful, isn't it?

600
00:41:51,960 --> 00:41:53,240
CYRIL: Mummy?

601
00:41:54,040 --> 00:41:55,640
See how it shines!

602
00:42:04,960 --> 00:42:06,400
Nice one, Madge, a complete write-off.

603
00:42:22,320 --> 00:42:25,600
The stars are going inside her.
She's taking the whole forest.

604
00:42:25,800 --> 00:42:28,040
Oh, this is marvellous.

605
00:42:28,200 --> 00:42:30,800
Oh, this is really quite wonderful.

606
00:42:40,120 --> 00:42:41,120
What...

607
00:42:44,520 --> 00:42:47,160
Madge? Are you all right?

608
00:42:47,760 --> 00:42:50,720
Talk to me. Madge, can you hear me?

609
00:42:51,440 --> 00:42:54,320
Yes, I can hear you.
I'm perfectly fine, thank you.

610
00:42:54,480 --> 00:42:55,600
Fine?

611
00:42:56,440 --> 00:42:58,800
You've got a whole world
inside your head!

612
00:42:58,880 --> 00:43:00,160
I know!

613
00:43:00,240 --> 00:43:02,840
It's funny, isn't it?
One can't imagine being a forest,

614
00:43:02,920 --> 00:43:04,800
then suddenly one can.

615
00:43:05,880 --> 00:43:08,760
-How remarkable.
-You're okay? She's okay?

616
00:43:10,320 --> 00:43:12,040
(IN DEEP VOICE) She is strong.

617
00:43:13,440 --> 00:43:15,440
(NORMAL VOICE) Ooh! That wasn't me.

618
00:43:16,440 --> 00:43:18,600
Oh, this is all really rather clever,
isn't it?

619
00:43:18,680 --> 00:43:20,960
She's strong? She's strong?

620
00:43:21,040 --> 00:43:26,360
Oh! Oh! Stupid me, stupid old Doctor.

621
00:43:26,560 --> 00:43:27,760
-Do you get it, Cyril?
-No.

622
00:43:27,840 --> 00:43:29,640
-Lily, you do, don't you?
-No.

623
00:43:29,720 --> 00:43:33,760
Course you do, think about it.
Weak and strong, it's a translation.

624
00:43:34,280 --> 00:43:36,360
Translated from
the base code of nature itself.

625
00:43:36,440 --> 00:43:38,360
You and I, Cyril, we're weak.

626
00:43:38,440 --> 00:43:43,040
But she's female.
More than female, she's Mum!

627
00:43:43,120 --> 00:43:46,840
How else does life ever travel?
The mother ship!

628
00:43:47,000 --> 00:43:48,840
(RUMBLING)

629
00:43:52,240 --> 00:43:53,920
(ENGINES FIRING)

630
00:43:55,080 --> 00:43:57,200
-What's happening?
-No idea. Do what I do.

631
00:43:57,280 --> 00:43:59,080
Hold tight and pretend it's a plan.

632
00:44:14,760 --> 00:44:17,640
-This is amazing.
-Where are we?

633
00:44:18,080 --> 00:44:21,640
Technically we're not anywhere,
we've flown into the time vortex.

634
00:44:22,080 --> 00:44:23,240
You've got what you wanted.

635
00:44:23,320 --> 00:44:25,000
Those idiots down there
can burn your old home

636
00:44:25,080 --> 00:44:26,120
and you'll be safe out here.

637
00:44:26,200 --> 00:44:29,320
But these people helped you
and they're in my protection.

638
00:44:29,600 --> 00:44:30,960
Now help them.

639
00:44:31,240 --> 00:44:32,960
How do we get home?

640
00:44:34,920 --> 00:44:37,040
-(IN DEEP VOICE) Think.
-Sorry, what?

641
00:44:37,880 --> 00:44:39,280
She must only think.

642
00:44:40,000 --> 00:44:42,720
Madge, did you hear that?
You said it, but did you hear it?

643
00:44:42,800 --> 00:44:46,160
-You've got to think.
-Think? What?

644
00:44:46,240 --> 00:44:48,360
Think of home, just picture it. Feel it!

645
00:44:48,720 --> 00:44:51,000
You have to really feel it!
Can you do that?

646
00:44:51,600 --> 00:44:53,440
Your mind is controlling this vessel.

647
00:44:53,520 --> 00:44:57,840
-You can fly us all back for Christmas.
-My head is full of trees, Caretaker.

648
00:44:57,920 --> 00:44:59,320
Can't you fly us home?

649
00:44:59,400 --> 00:45:00,800
I don't have a home to think of.

650
00:45:00,880 --> 00:45:02,640
And between you and me,
I'm older than I look

651
00:45:02,720 --> 00:45:05,240
and I can't feel the way you do,
not any more.

652
00:45:05,320 --> 00:45:08,880
And you really need to feel it, Madge.

653
00:45:09,040 --> 00:45:11,720
Everything about home that you miss,
till you can't bear it,

654
00:45:11,800 --> 00:45:14,520
-till you almost burst.
-Till it hurts?

655
00:45:15,840 --> 00:45:18,280
Is that what you mean, Caretaker?

656
00:45:18,880 --> 00:45:20,600
-Till it hurts?
-Yes.

657
00:45:21,600 --> 00:45:22,720
Yes.

658
00:45:34,440 --> 00:45:36,000
Well, then...

659
00:45:36,720 --> 00:45:39,600
home in time for Christmas! (GROANING)

660
00:45:48,000 --> 00:45:49,880
What's happening? Where are we going?

661
00:45:50,120 --> 00:45:52,680
Show them! Show them!

662
00:45:56,280 --> 00:45:58,320
Ha! The time vortex.

663
00:45:58,400 --> 00:46:02,280
Your mother is flying a forest
through the time vortex,

664
00:46:02,360 --> 00:46:03,760
be a little impressed!

665
00:46:03,960 --> 00:46:05,120
What are you going home for?

666
00:46:05,200 --> 00:46:07,680
What's pulling you there?
Please try. Please think.

667
00:46:09,520 --> 00:46:11,560
-Reg!
-Daddy!

668
00:46:12,400 --> 00:46:13,760
My Reg!

669
00:46:18,440 --> 00:46:21,640
That's it. Focus on Reg.
Be careful, but focus on him.

670
00:46:21,720 --> 00:46:24,640
-I don't... I don't know what...
-How did you meet?

671
00:46:24,720 --> 00:46:28,200
-You and Reg, tell me how you met.
-He followed me home.

672
00:46:29,640 --> 00:46:32,720
I worked in the dairy,
he always used to follow me home.

673
00:46:33,160 --> 00:46:35,240
Look at Father. He looks so young.

674
00:46:35,400 --> 00:46:38,640
He said he'd keep on following me
till I married him.

675
00:46:39,880 --> 00:46:41,280
Didn't like to make a scene.

676
00:46:41,360 --> 00:46:43,520
Just stay focused, think of home.

677
00:46:43,600 --> 00:46:44,920
This thing, it works psychically.

678
00:46:45,000 --> 00:46:47,120
-(WHIRRING)
-It'll find a signal and lock on.

679
00:46:47,720 --> 00:46:51,320
No. No, please don't show me that.
Please don't show me that!

680
00:46:51,440 --> 00:46:54,480
-Is that Daddy"s plane?
-Please, I don't want to see that!

681
00:46:54,560 --> 00:46:55,960
-Please!
-No, no, no, Madge.

682
00:46:56,040 --> 00:46:57,960
Don't break the signal now,
we can't break it now, I'm sorry.

683
00:46:58,040 --> 00:47:01,840
But not the night he died.
I don't want to see him die!

684
00:47:01,920 --> 00:47:03,280
(SOBBING)

685
00:47:04,560 --> 00:47:07,080
What do you mean "the night he died"?

686
00:47:07,160 --> 00:47:10,400
Oh, please don't make me watch him die!

687
00:47:10,480 --> 00:47:13,360
Mummy? Is Daddy dead?

688
00:47:14,720 --> 00:47:15,720
Mummy?

689
00:47:23,360 --> 00:47:27,080
Sir, Anderson's in a bad way.
Where are we?

690
00:47:27,160 --> 00:47:29,600
I don't know.
Somewhere over the Channel.

691
00:47:29,680 --> 00:47:31,800
What do I tell Anderson?

692
00:47:32,600 --> 00:47:35,080
Tell him... Tell him...
Tell him we're going home for Christmas.

693
00:47:35,560 --> 00:47:37,080
Yes, sir.

694
00:47:43,640 --> 00:47:45,320
I'm sorry, my love.

695
00:47:58,960 --> 00:48:01,000
MADGE: Goodbye, my love, goodbye!

696
00:48:13,640 --> 00:48:14,680
(GROANING)

697
00:48:14,760 --> 00:48:17,880
Cyril, Lily, are you all right?

698
00:48:18,640 --> 00:48:20,680
-LILY: Yeah.
-(WHIRRING)

699
00:48:22,360 --> 00:48:24,080
-Are they dead?
-No.

700
00:48:25,000 --> 00:48:28,440
They're just wood now.
They've been...emptied.

701
00:48:30,800 --> 00:48:32,640
The forest has gone
from your head, too, hasn't it?

702
00:48:32,720 --> 00:48:34,120
Where is it now?

703
00:48:34,200 --> 00:48:35,480
The life force of the whole forest

704
00:48:35,560 --> 00:48:39,120
has transmuted itself into
a sub-etheric waveband of light,

705
00:48:39,200 --> 00:48:40,960
which can exist as...

706
00:48:42,200 --> 00:48:46,440
The-The-The... The souls of the trees

707
00:48:46,520 --> 00:48:48,560
are out among the stars

708
00:48:48,640 --> 00:48:50,720
and they're shining, very happy.

709
00:48:51,640 --> 00:48:53,480
And you got them there.

710
00:48:53,560 --> 00:48:55,120
Well done, Madge.

711
00:48:56,440 --> 00:48:57,840
And where are we?

712
00:48:58,120 --> 00:48:59,800
Home! Christmas morning.

713
00:49:01,600 --> 00:49:04,520
We've taken a bit of a shortcut,
haven't you always wanted to do that?

714
00:49:04,800 --> 00:49:06,000
Mother?

715
00:49:06,680 --> 00:49:08,280
Oh, look at you.

716
00:49:09,160 --> 00:49:11,280
You've been so brave, you...

717
00:49:12,640 --> 00:49:14,680
Look, we're home again, see?

718
00:49:15,200 --> 00:49:17,600
What did you mean, "watch him die"?

719
00:49:19,720 --> 00:49:22,880
Where's Father? Where is he?
Where's Daddy?

720
00:49:27,640 --> 00:49:29,040
Why are you holding a telegram?

721
00:49:34,360 --> 00:49:36,000
What does it say?

722
00:49:36,720 --> 00:49:40,120
-Please just tell us.
-Tell us!

723
00:49:42,000 --> 00:49:44,360
I imagine you'd prefer to be alone.

724
00:49:44,880 --> 00:49:47,600
I don't believe anyone
would prefer that.

725
00:49:48,600 --> 00:49:50,440
Stay close, Caretaker.

726
00:49:50,720 --> 00:49:52,560
I'll be right outside.

727
00:49:58,760 --> 00:50:01,960
Lily, Cyril.

728
00:50:14,920 --> 00:50:17,680
A few nights ago, your father,
who, as you know,

729
00:50:17,760 --> 00:50:21,120
was the best of men
and the bravest of pilots

730
00:50:21,200 --> 00:50:23,120
was flying home for Christmas.

731
00:50:24,920 --> 00:50:29,400
His plane was badly damaged
and his instruments failed him.

732
00:50:31,640 --> 00:50:34,840
Unfortunately, he was flying on
a night where there was no moon

733
00:50:34,920 --> 00:50:38,440
and because it was very cloudy,
there were no stars to...

734
00:50:42,440 --> 00:50:44,720
there were no stars to light his way.

735
00:50:46,160 --> 00:50:50,360
-Did he get lost?
-Yes, Cyril. He got so very lost.

736
00:50:51,520 --> 00:50:53,880
Um, sorry to interrupt.

737
00:50:54,480 --> 00:50:56,360
But you might want to pop out here
for a moment.

738
00:50:56,440 --> 00:50:58,520
Caretaker, I'm talking to my children!

739
00:50:58,600 --> 00:51:02,840
I know, and before you go any further,
I think you'd better come and look.

740
00:51:12,000 --> 00:51:14,080
No stars to light the way, Madge?

741
00:51:14,160 --> 00:51:15,920
There was one.

742
00:51:17,720 --> 00:51:19,160
There was you!

743
00:51:24,440 --> 00:51:26,440
-What is it?
-I don't know.

744
00:51:27,080 --> 00:51:29,840
But it's all we've got.
We can follow it!

745
00:51:37,240 --> 00:51:41,160
Madge Arwell, who flew a whole forest
though the time vortex,

746
00:51:41,280 --> 00:51:43,160
plus one husband.

747
00:51:43,400 --> 00:51:45,320
He did it again, Madge.
He followed you home.

748
00:51:45,760 --> 00:51:47,320
Look what you can do!

749
00:51:48,320 --> 00:51:49,560
Mother Christmas!

750
00:51:50,560 --> 00:51:53,720
Madge! What am I doing here?

751
00:51:54,400 --> 00:51:57,560
It's Christmas Day, my love,
where else would you be?

752
00:51:57,640 --> 00:52:00,160
Christmas Day? How?

753
00:52:00,520 --> 00:52:02,280
We took a short-cut.

754
00:52:07,600 --> 00:52:09,280
CHILDREN: Daddy!

755
00:52:25,240 --> 00:52:26,720
Happy crying.

756
00:52:29,080 --> 00:52:30,560
Humany-wumany.

757
00:52:32,560 --> 00:52:33,880
-Oh, yes!
-Yeah.

758
00:52:38,560 --> 00:52:39,880
(CHATTING, INDISTINCT)

759
00:52:56,360 --> 00:53:00,400
-Ah!
-Of course! It's you, isn't it?

760
00:53:01,320 --> 00:53:03,680
My spaceman angel
with his head on backwards!

761
00:53:03,760 --> 00:53:05,880
How do I look the right way round?

762
00:53:06,280 --> 00:53:07,440
Funnier.

763
00:53:07,560 --> 00:53:09,240
-Okay.
-So you came back.

764
00:53:09,320 --> 00:53:11,720
Well, you were there for me
when I had a bad day.

765
00:53:11,920 --> 00:53:13,320
Always like to return a favour.

766
00:53:13,400 --> 00:53:18,320
Got a bit glitchy in the middle there,
but it sort of worked out in the end.

767
00:53:20,520 --> 00:53:22,160
Story of my life.

768
00:53:23,280 --> 00:53:24,600
Thank you.

769
00:53:27,680 --> 00:53:31,360
Oh, you did it all yourself,
Madge Arwell.

770
00:53:32,120 --> 00:53:33,360
But thanks for thanking me.

771
00:53:33,440 --> 00:53:36,920
Now, the last time I saw you,
I went back the next day

772
00:53:37,080 --> 00:53:38,600
but the police box had gone.

773
00:53:38,680 --> 00:53:40,520
Yeah. You want to see how it's done?

774
00:53:40,680 --> 00:53:41,680
No.

775
00:53:42,160 --> 00:53:45,120
I want you to stay
for Christmas, please.

776
00:53:45,200 --> 00:53:47,200
Ah, well, you see,
things to do, people to see.

777
00:53:47,280 --> 00:53:50,360
Ah. Of course, yes, family of your own.

778
00:53:50,800 --> 00:53:52,000
Well...

779
00:53:53,040 --> 00:53:54,720
-No, actually.
-Oh.

780
00:53:54,920 --> 00:53:56,880
Yes, yes, you said you had no family.

781
00:53:57,280 --> 00:53:59,960
But there must be people
who love you, friends.

782
00:54:00,040 --> 00:54:03,840
No. Well, yes, but it's a long story.

783
00:54:05,040 --> 00:54:07,080
But they all think I'm dead.

784
00:54:07,560 --> 00:54:10,040
Never mind, anyway,
watch my box do its thing.

785
00:54:10,120 --> 00:54:11,640
It's really cool, you'll love it.

786
00:54:11,840 --> 00:54:13,600
No, no one should be alone
at Christmas.

787
00:54:13,680 --> 00:54:15,360
I'm fine, I don't mind.
I'm really very good at...

788
00:54:15,440 --> 00:54:17,880
I'm not talking about you.
I'm talking about your friends.

789
00:54:17,960 --> 00:54:20,000
You can't let them think that
you're dead, not at Christmas.

790
00:54:20,080 --> 00:54:24,520
-It's complicated, very complicated...
-You must go and tell them, at once.

791
00:54:24,600 --> 00:54:25,960
Off you go.

792
00:54:28,640 --> 00:54:31,000
Yes, Mum. I'll think about it.

793
00:54:39,120 --> 00:54:40,760
Now, eyes on the box.

794
00:54:41,520 --> 00:54:43,040
Oh, Caretaker?

795
00:54:44,000 --> 00:54:46,080
What if I require you again?

796
00:54:46,320 --> 00:54:47,720
Make a wish.

797
00:54:52,240 --> 00:54:53,680
(WHOOSHING)

798
00:55:10,640 --> 00:55:12,560
What the hell was that?

799
00:55:12,760 --> 00:55:16,120
Oh, it was just the Caretaker
returning to the time vortex.

800
00:55:16,640 --> 00:55:19,040
It's a lovely place,
I've been there myself.

801
00:55:19,440 --> 00:55:21,160
Shall we go downstairs?

802
00:55:28,480 --> 00:55:31,040
AMY: (GROANING)
If that is more carol singers,

803
00:55:31,120 --> 00:55:32,680
I have a water pistol!

804
00:55:32,760 --> 00:55:35,280
You don't want to be all wet
on a night like this...

805
00:55:41,120 --> 00:55:44,880
I'm not absolutely sure how long...

806
00:55:45,480 --> 00:55:46,680
Two years?

807
00:55:50,840 --> 00:55:53,080
Okay. Fair point.

808
00:55:53,360 --> 00:55:57,320
-So, you're not dead.
-And a Happy New Year!

809
00:56:01,840 --> 00:56:03,320
River told us.

810
00:56:04,760 --> 00:56:07,600
-Well, of course she did.
-She's a good girl.

811
00:56:09,320 --> 00:56:13,280
-Well? I'm not going to hug first.
-Nor am 1.

812
00:56:33,000 --> 00:56:34,400
(BOTH LAUGHING)

813
00:56:45,080 --> 00:56:48,440
Oh! Mr Pond!
Guess who's coming for dinner?

814
00:56:49,440 --> 00:56:52,040
Ohhh. You're not dead, then?

815
00:56:52,120 --> 00:56:53,600
-We've done that.
-Oh.

816
00:56:53,680 --> 00:56:56,200
We're about to have Christmas dinner.
Joining us?

817
00:56:56,720 --> 00:56:58,520
-If it's no trouble.
-There's a place set for you.

818
00:56:58,600 --> 00:57:00,560
But you didn't know I was coming.
Why would you set me a place?

819
00:57:00,640 --> 00:57:02,640
Oh, because we always do.

820
00:57:04,640 --> 00:57:06,680
It's Christmas, you moron.

821
00:57:08,800 --> 00:57:10,040
Come on.

